---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Corpus from '../components/Corpus.astro';
import Coverage from '../components/Coverage.astro';
import { withBase } from '../lib/url';
---

<Base
  title="Purple corpus"
  description="Every attack, beside its detection. An ATT&CK-tagged, red↔blue paired corpus spanning on-prem AD, cloud IAM, Kubernetes, CI/CD (GitHub, GitLab, Jenkins), Harbor, Vault, Terraform, and Snowflake — authored in htpx, executed from dotfiles-Kali, detected by dotfiles-Defense."
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head">
        <span class="eyebrow">Purple team</span>
        <h1>Every attack, beside its detection</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          The role layers are two halves of one loop. <strong>dotfiles-Kali</strong> runs the
          attack; <strong>dotfiles-Defense</strong> ships the Sigma rule that catches it. The
          pairing itself is the source of truth: it lives in
          <a href="https://github.com/dotgibson/htpx" target="_blank" rel="noopener">htpx</a>
          as ATT&CK-tagged red↔blue entries, and this table is generated straight from them.
        </p>
        <p class="lead mt">
          Each row is a technique you can execute on demand from Kali and confirm firing in
          Defense — the purple loop closed in a single line. Filter by platform, and follow a
          badge to its ATT&CK page. See the
          <a href={withBase('/architecture')}>three-layer architecture →</a> for how the
          layers fit together.
        </p>
      </div>

      <Corpus />

      <div class="cov-head">
        <h2>What the blue side actually detects</h2>
        <p class="lead">
          The other half of the loop: the Sigma rules <strong>dotfiles-Defense</strong> ships,
          rolled up across the ATT&CK matrix. Every rule is drift-gated in CI and generates its
          own <a href="https://mitre-attack.github.io/attack-navigator/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
            >ATT&CK Navigator</a
          > layer plus a <code>COVERAGE.md</code> report — this is that same roll-up, live.
        </p>
      </div>

      <Coverage />

      <p class="corpus-foot">
        The corpus is generated from the htpx <code>entries/</code> by
        <code>scripts/collect-corpus.mjs</code>, and the coverage roll-up is generated from the
        <a href="https://github.com/dotgibson/dotfiles-Defense" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
          >dotfiles-Defense</a
        > Sigma rules by <code>scripts/collect-coverage.mjs</code> (mirroring that repo's
        drift-gated <code>gen-coverage.sh</code>). Neither is hand-typed.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .corpus-foot {
    margin-top: 2rem;
    padding-top: 1.25rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--text-dim);
  }
  .mt {
    margin-top: 0.75rem;
  }
  .cov-head {
    margin: 3rem 0 1.75rem;
    padding-top: 2rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
  }
  .cov-head h2 {
    margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
  }
</style>
